    <descriptionText><![CDATA[<Introtext style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; color:#cc0033; margin:10px; padding:0 0 0 5px; background:#e8e8e8; border-bottom:1px solid #333; display:block;">Collecting Information and Determining Next Steps</Introtext><welcomeText style=" font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:18pt; text-align:justify; font-weight:normal; color:#333; display:block; margin:0 10px 10px">This is an Options question, not an Execute Next Steps question. It is too general at this point in the discussion and moves the conversation backwards.<BR><BR>
        
        The best question is, “As a hospitalist, I know you see SIADH, cirrhosis, and heart failure patients who present with hyponatremia.  I’d like to set a time to share more specifically with you about Samsca, and potentially also arrange a time to continue that conversation with Pharmacy or Dr. Rivers, a nephrologist who regularly prescribes Samsca.  When would be a good time to meet again?”<BR><BR>
        
        This Execute Next Steps question makes a clear advance, while framing the question in a way that demonstrates your understanding of Dr. Chu’s key priorities.<BR><BR>
        
        <B> It will help you to know the answer to this question to continue.  Here is how Dr. Chu would have answered:</B> <BR><BR>
        
        “That sounds like a good next step.  Come back a couple weeks from now, and I’ll be happy to talk again.”</welcomeText>]]></descriptionText>
